# Security Standards (Healthcare)

## PII & Health Data
- **Never** log patient names, fiscal codes, diagnoses, or any health-related data
- **Never** expose PII in error messages or API responses beyond what's needed
- Sensitive model attributes encrypted with Active Record Encryption
- Keys managed via Rails credentials (never in env or code)

## Authorization
- Every controller action in `backoffice/` is covered by `verify_authorized` (set in `Backoffice::ApplicationController`)
- Use `authorize!` explicitly when policy check is conditional
- Skip only with `skip_verify_authorized if: :devise_controller?`
- Scope queries: use `authorized_scope(Model.all)` not raw queries

## Strong Parameters
- Always explicit `params.require().permit()` — never `permit!` or `params.to_h`
- Separate permit lists for create vs update when fields differ

## SQL Injection Prevention
- Use parameterized queries, ActiveRecord scopes, or Arel
- Never interpolate user input into SQL strings

## CSRF
- Standard Rails CSRF protection for HTML controllers
- API controllers: `protect_from_forgery with: :null_session` (token auth instead)
- Webhooks: verify signatures (Landbot, SurveyJS) before processing

## Dependency Security
- Run before every release: `bin/bundler-audit --update`
- Run for JS: `bin/importmap audit`
- Brakeman in CI with `-w2` (warn level 2): `bin/brakeman -q -w2`

## Secrets
- All secrets via Rails credentials or env vars (see `.env.sample`)
- Never commit `.env`, `master.key`, or credential files
